# Project: JUCE WebView MIDI Plugin

## What This Is

A JUCE 8 VST3 plugin with an embedded web UI (WebBrowserComponent). The plugin acts as a MIDI generator — a Three.js-based visual environment runs in the web view, and events in that environment produce MIDI notes that get sent to the DAW (Ableton Live) via a lock-free ring buffer on the audio thread.

Users route the plugin's MIDI output to another track with a synth to hear the notes.

## Architecture

### C++ Layer (rarely changes)
- `PluginProcessor` — audio thread, transport state (atomics), lock-free MIDI queue (AbstractFifo)
- `PluginEditor` — hosts WebBrowserComponent, bridges JS ↔ C++, serves web assets from BinaryData via resource provider

### Web Layer (where all creative work happens)
- `shell.js` — owns Three.js renderer/scene/camera, animation loop, experiment lifecycle, MIDI API, scale system, experiment selector UI, key/scale selector UI
- One `.js` file per experiment at `web/` root (filename must match the experiment's `id`, e.g. `graph.js` registers as `'graph'`). `shell.js` dynamically loads each entry from its `EXPERIMENTS` manifest.

### Experiment Contract
Every experiment is an object with:
- `id`, `name`, `description` (metadata)
- `init(context)` — called once on first activation
- `update(delta, transport)` — called every frame by the shell
- `pause()`, `resume()`, `destroy()` — lifecycle hooks

The `context` object provides:
- `scene` — THREE.Scene
- `camera` — THREE.OrthographicCamera
- `renderer` — THREE.WebGLRenderer (read-only)
- `midi.sendNoteOn(note, velocity, channel)`
- `midi.sendNoteOff(note, channel)`
- `midi.sendNote(note, velocity, channel, durationMs)`
- `scale.getNotesInRange(low, high)` — get valid MIDI notes in current key/scale
- `scale.getNoteForDegree(degree, octave)` — get MIDI note by scale degree
- `scale.getScaleDegree(midiNote)` — get degree for a MIDI note
- `scale.onChange(callback)` — subscribe to key/scale changes, returns unsubscribe fn
- `scale.getKey()` — returns { root, scaleName }
- `getTransport()` — returns { tempo, beatPosition, timeSigNumerator, timeSigDenominator, isPlaying }
- `getSize()` — returns { width, height }

Experiments do NOT call requestAnimationFrame or renderer.render(). The shell handles both.

## Prototyping Workflow

There is a dedicated experiment file for prototyping: `web/test.js`

This is the scratchpad. All new ideas start here. The flow is:

1. **Prototype in test.js.** Iterate fast, break things, try ideas. Don't worry about clean code.
2. **When an idea is ready to keep:** Duplicate test.js to a new file at `web/` root with a descriptive name (e.g. `ascending-walk.js`). Add an entry for it to the `EXPERIMENTS` manifest in `shell.js` (`{ id, name, description }`) — `id` must match the filename without `.js`. Register it with `Shell.register(id, behavior)`. CMake's `file(GLOB web/*.js)` picks it up automatically; no edits to `CMakeLists.txt` or `index.html` needed.
3. **Reset test.js** back to the blank template (see below) for the next idea.

When I say "let's try something" or "prototype this" — work in test.js.
When I say "let's keep this" or "package this up" — duplicate to a new file and reset test.js.
When I say "new idea" or "start fresh" — reset test.js to the blank template.

### Blank Test Template

When resetting test.js, use this skeleton:

```javascript
const TestExperiment = {
  id: 'test',
  name: 'Test',
  description: 'Prototyping scratchpad',

  _group: null,
  _context: null,
  _unsubscribeScale: null,

  init(context) {
    this._context = context;
    this._group = new THREE.Group();
    context.scene.add(this._group);

    this._unsubscribeScale = context.scale.onChange(() => {
      this._rebuild();
    });

    this._rebuild();
  },

  _rebuild() {
    // Clear existing objects
    while (this._group.children.length) {
      this._group.remove(this._group.children[0]);
    }

    const notes = this._context.scale.getNotesInRange(48, 72);
    // Build your scene here using notes array
  },

  update(delta, transport) {
    // Called every frame — update positions, check triggers, etc.
  },

  pause() {},
  resume() {},

  destroy() {
    if (this._unsubscribeScale) this._unsubscribeScale();
  },
};

Shell.register(TestExperiment);
```

## File Structure

```
web/
├── index.html
├── three.min.js
├── matter.min.js          # available if an experiment needs physics
├── shell.js
├── test.js                # always exists, prototyping scratchpad
├── graph.js               # finalized experiments live alongside shell.js
├── scribbler.js
└── ...
```

## Key Rules

- **Never modify the C++ layer** unless explicitly asked. All creative work is in the web layer.
- **The shell owns the render loop.** Experiments implement update(), they don't manage their own animation frames.
- **Scale-aware:** Use context.scale to get valid notes. Never hardcode note values. Always subscribe to scale changes and rebuild when the key changes.
- **MIDI only:** Experiments produce MIDI events, not audio. Sound comes from whatever synth the user has on the receiving track in Ableton.
- **Dark aesthetic:** Keep visuals dark-themed, minimal, clean.
